ers or to take better care of herself so that she can take care of others. Dana Becker argues that ideas like empowerment perpetuate the myth that many of the problems women have are medical rather than societal; personal rather than political.From mesmerism to psychotherapy to the Oprah Winfrey Show, women have gleaned ideas about who they are as psychological beings. Becker questions what women have had to gain from these ideas as she recounts the story of where they have been led and where the therapeutic culture is taking them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPower (Social sciences). 0aWomen and psychoanalysis. 0aWomenxMental healthxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aWomenxMental healthzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh  aEmpowerment.  aMyth.  abeen.  acentury.  acultureboth.  agrowing.  ahave.  ainfluenced.  amid-nineteenth.  apopular.  apresent.  aprofessionalfrom.  arapidly.  arepresented.  asurveys.  atherapeutic.  aways.  awhich.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814738405423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814738405/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK